NAME
    su(1)		- superimpose another user's shell

SYNOPSIS
    su  [ username ]

DESCRIPTION
    This performs a log-in of another user, a new process is
    used for the appropriate shell. Your current shell is not
    destroyed, as occurs when using login(1).

    If "username" is not given it defaults to "root" (the super-
    user). A password will be asked for if "username" requires one.

    The group and user id are changed for the new username.
    The environment entries $HOME and $SHELL are set up according
    to the new username's entry in the password file, but the
    rest of the environment is passed untouched. The current
    directory is not changed.

FILES
    /etc/passwd

SEE ALSO
    login(1)
